<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
This topic has come up on several threads here, recently, and the general consensus is this:<P>Bards do everything.<P>We don't do it as well as a 'pure' version of the class, but usually well enough. We can melee (dual weild), just not tank too well, we buff, debuff, DD, DoT, charm, mezz, snare, haste, slow, fear, invis, damage shield, regen, clarity, etc. etc. Most all of our buffing songs affect the entire group. In addition, we do all of these things mana-free!(With a couple of small exceptions.) The drawback is we can only really do about 3 of these things at once, so there's a good bit of strategy to playing a bard.<P>Bards are made to fill any role that might be missing from a party. Admittedly, we fill some roles (enchanter) better than others (cleric), but we can do most anything in a pinch.<P>Further, bards are also party enhancers. We're a catalyst that makes a fair group good and a good group great. We drastically reduce downtime and keep a group functioning at peak efficiency.<P>A well-played bard is essential to any good group. Some may say they can do without, and I suppose you can. But why would you want to?   <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>As for stats: STR, DEX, and CHA. Strength because we're a plate-wearing class and need it to wear the heavy armor, DEX to help avoid missed notes (fizzles), and Charisma for our Mezz, Charm, Fear etc. songs.<P>Hope this helps!<P>--------------------<P><A HREF="http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=57639" TARGET=_blank>Devamaru Silverlight</A><BR>Torvonnilous
</FONT>
