You have a 60 cha?! How'd you pull THAT off? The three races that can be bards all start with a higher charisma than that. Put the Staff of Writhing down when you're charm fighting, bud. Oy.<P>At any rate, Deva hit it pretty much on the nose. If you can name a function, there's a prety good chance bards can do it, if not do it well. The only thing that we tend to be asked to do that we aren't equipped to do is tank. We only qualify as "tanks" in comparison to pure casters. Even monks make better tanks than bards do.<P>I've been gaming in one form or another for a very long time (15 years or so), and I'll tell you this...of all the game systems I've seen, EQ is the ONLY game where bards can (and do) end up as the most powerful class (from a PvP standpoint, anyway). Even in the normal, mob-killing mode, bards can solo things other people can only dream of taking solo. Put us in a group, though, and the whole party can do things it couldn't do before.<P>There is no single class that's harder to play well than a bard. The other side of that coin, though, is that there's no single class that brings more to a fight than a bard. There are very few bard main characters, and even fewer high level bards, due mainly to how complicated a bard is to play (and the pervasive misconception that bards suck). So, if you like to be different, playing a bard to high levels is a good way to go.<P>--------------------<P>Tinolan<BR>Minstrel of Epic Adventurers<BR>Fennin Ro
